00:52:17.140 --> 00:52:17.790
I'm sorry?

00:52:17.790 --> 00:52:19.956
AUDIENCE: How much, like
the differences in empathy,

00:52:19.956 --> 00:52:22.340
like how much you empathize
with someone else.

00:52:22.340 --> 00:52:24.924
Is there any studies on
the different types of--

00:52:24.924 --> 00:52:26.590
HOWARD ROSS: Oh, you
mean in other words

00:52:26.590 --> 00:52:28.450
does one race trigger
empathy less than others?

00:52:28.450 --> 00:52:28.740
AUDIENCE: Yeah, exactly.

00:52:28.740 --> 00:52:30.170
HOWARD ROSS: I
don't know of that.

00:52:30.170 --> 00:52:32.610
But my suspicion would
be, based on my experience

00:52:32.610 --> 00:52:34.550
of working with
this in other areas,

00:52:34.550 --> 00:52:37.415
is that it probably relates
more to your own background

00:52:37.415 --> 00:52:39.040
and how those racial
dynamics showed up

00:52:39.040 --> 00:52:41.844
in your particular
community or the structure

00:52:41.844 --> 00:52:43.010
around you when you grew up.

00:52:43.010 --> 00:52:44.530
So if you grow up
in an environment,

00:52:44.530 --> 00:52:47.630
let's say in the United States,
where the race conversation

00:52:47.630 --> 00:52:49.570
has most dramatically
been defined

00:52:49.570 --> 00:52:52.530
between black and white, it
probably is stronger there,

00:52:52.530 --> 00:52:55.260
which is one of the
reasons why Latinos

00:52:55.260 --> 00:52:58.212
and Asians and Native
Americans, for example, often

00:52:58.212 --> 00:52:59.670
feel left out of
that conversation.

00:52:59.670 --> 00:53:02.870
Because we tend to
look at the extremes.

00:53:02.870 --> 00:53:05.874
But we do know that race is the
first thing that the human mind

00:53:05.874 --> 00:53:08.540
responds to when we look at each
other, which really makes sense

00:53:08.540 --> 00:53:12.884
if you think about it, because
gender, for example, almost

00:53:12.884 --> 00:53:15.300
everybody has had some intimate
relationship with somebody

00:53:15.300 --> 00:53:17.405
of the opposite
gender, but many of us

00:53:17.405 --> 00:53:19.780
do not necessarily have any
kind of intimate relationship

00:53:19.780 --> 00:53:21.450
with somebody of
the opposite race.

00:53:21.450 --> 00:53:23.419
So it's the first
identifier that we see,

00:53:23.419 --> 00:53:25.210
and therefore the first
protective reaction

00:53:25.210 --> 00:53:26.470
we tend to come up with.

00:53:26.470 --> 00:53:28.890
The other thing is
that, of course,

00:53:28.890 --> 00:53:31.374
because of
internalized bias-- we

00:53:31.374 --> 00:53:33.040
used to call it
internalized oppression.

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:35.520
It's now often called
stereotyped threat.

00:53:35.520 --> 00:53:38.240
We internalize the messages
about people like us.

00:53:38.240 --> 00:53:41.110
For example, when they do the
implicit association test,

00:53:41.110 --> 00:53:43.530
they find that if you do
the implicit association

00:53:43.530 --> 00:53:46.960
test between whites and
blacks, that something

00:53:46.960 --> 00:53:50.580
like 75% of whites will
more positively associate

00:53:50.580 --> 00:53:52.889
with whites than blacks,
but a majority of blacks

00:53:52.889 --> 00:53:54.930
will also associate with
whites more than blacks,

00:53:54.930 --> 00:53:57.390
because they've internalized
the same negative stereotypes

00:53:57.390 --> 00:53:58.930
about people like them.

00:53:58.930 --> 00:54:01.340
So the key here is to
recognize that even when

00:54:01.340 --> 00:54:03.990
we're good people and we
think we're being fair,

00:54:03.990 --> 00:54:06.940
we may have a tendency to
have less identification.

00:54:06.940 --> 00:54:09.740
And if we put this in the
context of the Fisk and Cuddy

00:54:09.740 --> 00:54:16.330
work warmth and competence,
the way that cam show up is,

00:54:16.330 --> 00:54:19.535
I may have warmth for you,
but my empathetic response

00:54:19.535 --> 00:54:21.660
may not be in being sensitive
to the competence you

00:54:21.660 --> 00:54:23.440
bring to the conversation.

00:54:23.440 --> 00:54:24.940
And this is hard
for us, those of us

00:54:24.940 --> 00:54:26.523
who are progressives
and see ourselves

00:54:26.523 --> 00:54:28.190
as really progressive
on this issue.

00:54:28.190 --> 00:54:29.355
I tell you, my
experience has been

00:54:29.355 --> 00:54:31.479
that working with organizations
that see themselves

00:54:31.479 --> 00:54:34.580
as progressive is sometimes more
challenging rather than less

00:54:34.580 --> 00:54:37.550
challenging around these issues,
because we identify as seeing

00:54:37.550 --> 00:54:40.020
ourselves as the good people,
the ones who have this

00:54:40.020 --> 00:54:41.930
handled, and are
less likely to be

00:54:41.930 --> 00:54:43.600
able to look at
things in ourselves.

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:46.240
Whereas when we go into really
conservative organizations,

00:54:46.240 --> 00:54:47.360
they say, I don't know
anything about this.

00:54:47.360 --> 00:54:48.194
Teach me what to do.

00:54:48.194 --> 00:54:49.735
They are very clear
that they haven't

00:54:49.735 --> 00:54:51.109
paid any attention to this.

00:54:51.109 --> 00:54:53.400
And so that's why organizations
in progressive-thinking

00:54:53.400 --> 00:54:56.140
organizations like
Google have to especially

00:54:56.140 --> 00:54:58.580
keep your nose to the
grindstone, so to speak,

00:54:58.580 --> 00:55:00.082
in terms of
continuing to develop

00:55:00.082 --> 00:55:01.540
that mindfulness
around this topic.

00:55:01.540 --> 00:55:05.320
Because our success,
our competence

00:55:05.320 --> 00:55:08.330
can blind us to the places
we still have work to do.

00:55:08.330 --> 00:55:10.930
And this is not a
place we get to.

00:55:10.930 --> 00:55:12.230
It's a like exercise.

00:55:12.230 --> 00:55:13.477
You never get there.

00:55:13.477 --> 00:55:15.560
If you build it into your
life on a regular basis,

00:55:15.560 --> 00:55:17.350
you know that it will
maintain your health,

00:55:17.350 --> 00:55:18.240
but if you think
you're just going

00:55:18.240 --> 00:55:20.114
to exercise until you
get yourself into shape

00:55:20.114 --> 00:55:22.560
and then stop, you know
how that works out.

00:55:22.560 --> 00:55:25.954
Seems like at my age, two
minutes later I'm out of shape.

00:55:25.954 --> 00:55:28.120
AUDIENCE: One of the largest
concerns with diversity

00:55:28.120 --> 00:55:30.670
training is the
potential for backlash,

00:55:30.670 --> 00:55:34.620
especially among individuals
who feel like they are not

00:55:34.620 --> 00:55:35.900
benefiting from the training.

00:55:35.900 --> 00:55:36.608
HOWARD ROSS: Yes.

00:55:36.608 --> 00:55:40.320
AUDIENCE: So given this concern,
what are some recommendations

00:55:40.320 --> 00:55:43.490
that you would recommend
when giving diversity

00:55:43.490 --> 00:55:45.480
trainings to ensure that
it is something that

00:55:45.480 --> 00:55:47.000
is inclusive for all employees?

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:47.750
HOWARD ROSS: Yeah.

00:55:47.750 --> 00:55:50.020
It's a great question.

00:55:50.020 --> 00:55:52.140
And it goes back
to the point I made

00:55:52.140 --> 00:55:54.140
before about sort of the
traditional diversity

00:55:54.140 --> 00:55:56.400
training, which has largely
been aimed at people,

00:55:56.400 --> 00:55:57.983
certain groups of
people, particularly

00:55:57.983 --> 00:56:00.092
people who look
like this, frankly.

00:56:00.092 --> 00:56:01.800
Diversity training is
to teach white guys

00:56:01.800 --> 00:56:06.160
to be more inclusive,
more whatever.

00:56:06.160 --> 00:56:09.086
I'm Jewish, and I
know Jewish people

00:56:09.086 --> 00:56:10.710
who rail against
anti-Semitism and make

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:11.820
a questionable racial comment.

00:56:11.820 --> 00:56:13.960
I know African Americans who
rail against racism and then

00:56:13.960 --> 00:56:15.910
make a homophobic or
heterosexist comment.

00:56:15.910 --> 00:56:19.006
I know LGBT folks who
rail against that and then

00:56:19.006 --> 00:56:20.880
make a questionable
comment about immigrants.

00:56:20.880 --> 00:56:22.440
We've all got something
going on with somebody.

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:24.231
And I think one of the
things we need to do

00:56:24.231 --> 00:56:25.935
is to speak to the
universality of that.

00:56:25.935 --> 00:56:30.710
That doesn't mean that all
biases are the same, because we

00:56:30.710 --> 00:56:34.240
know that there's certain biases
that are systemically supported

00:56:34.240 --> 00:56:37.720
by society or by an
organizational system.

00:56:37.720 --> 00:56:40.370
And so even though
an individual may

00:56:40.370 --> 00:56:42.084
have prejudice
against somebody else,

00:56:42.084 --> 00:56:43.500
it's different to
have a prejudice

00:56:43.500 --> 00:56:46.180
than it is to have a bias
or an -ism, as we might say,

00:56:46.180 --> 00:56:47.960
which is systemically supported.

00:56:47.960 --> 00:56:50.210
But this is why it's
so important for us

00:56:50.210 --> 00:56:52.990
to remove this sort of good
person/bad person fixing

00:56:52.990 --> 00:56:54.370
mindset.

00:56:54.370 --> 00:56:55.990
One of the reasons
that people are

00:56:55.990 --> 00:56:59.050
hesitant to get involved
in diversity work-- there's

00:56:59.050 --> 00:57:00.661
a powerful sense of
diversity fatigue

00:57:00.661 --> 00:57:02.160
out there-- is
because so much of it

00:57:02.160 --> 00:57:05.590
feels like people are having
their finger waved at you.

00:57:05.590 --> 00:57:08.270
And you're being told
to be a better person,

00:57:08.270 --> 00:57:09.920
and I'm here to fix you.

00:57:09.920 --> 00:57:13.790
And so things like inviting
people from dominant groups

00:57:13.790 --> 00:57:16.414
into these conversations,
building a strong business

00:57:16.414 --> 00:57:17.580
case, getting people to see.

00:57:17.580 --> 00:57:19.830
It's much easier-- when I
started doing the work close

00:57:19.830 --> 00:57:22.450
to 30 years ago now,
we didn't have data.

00:57:22.450 --> 00:57:25.435
Now we have data to
show that research shows

00:57:25.435 --> 00:57:26.810
that you get more
diverse people,

00:57:26.810 --> 00:57:28.890
you get better innovation, you
get better problem solving.

00:57:28.890 --> 00:57:31.100
Research shows that the
market shares are shifting,

00:57:31.100 --> 00:57:32.640
and we know these
demographics are changing.

00:57:32.640 --> 00:57:33.820
You need to reach
that market share.

00:57:33.820 --> 00:57:35.934
So it's pretty easy to
build a business case now

00:57:35.934 --> 00:57:38.350
and to get people to realize
this is not for those people.

00:57:38.350 --> 00:57:39.670
It's for all of us.

00:57:39.670 --> 00:57:42.790
And that's got to be a
constant conversation.

00:57:42.790 --> 00:57:45.350
And then the second piece
of that is, for those of us

00:57:45.350 --> 00:57:48.270
who are practitioners, when we
get that resistance, when we're

00:57:48.270 --> 00:57:50.650
sensing that resistance,
rather than point

00:57:50.650 --> 00:57:53.856
fingers at the resistors and
say, why are they resisting?

00:57:53.856 --> 00:57:55.480
To start asking
ourselves the question,

00:57:55.480 --> 00:57:57.605
what are we doing to
contribute to that resistance?

00:57:57.605 --> 00:57:59.320
What can we do
differently to invite them

00:57:59.320 --> 00:58:00.740
into the conversation?

00:58:00.740 --> 00:58:02.931
Because it's very easy--
and I've been there before.

00:58:02.931 --> 00:58:04.930
You feel sometimes like
you're beating your head

00:58:04.930 --> 00:58:06.790
against a brick wall
when you're trying

00:58:06.790 --> 00:58:09.200
to get people into
the conversation.

00:58:09.200 --> 00:58:11.540
But it's very easy to
make them the problem.

00:58:11.540 --> 00:58:14.230
But the reality is, we must be
contributing something for them

00:58:14.230 --> 00:58:15.970
not to be welcomed
into the conversation.

00:58:15.970 --> 00:58:17.470
And so to find ways
where we can get

00:58:17.470 --> 00:58:20.134
more folks into the
conversation so that it's not

00:58:20.134 --> 00:58:21.550
one group talking
to another group

00:58:21.550 --> 00:58:24.890
but rather a collective group
sharing it with everybody

00:58:24.890 --> 00:58:26.994
in the organization
or the system.

00:58:26.994 --> 00:58:28.160
ELIZABETH CURTIS: All right.

00:58:28.160 --> 00:58:30.870
Well, thank you so much for
being here with us today.

